A painting, painted by an artist, in an episode of a season of a show, containing a specific feature.

We could also use REGULAR EXPRESSIONS to extract the digit pattern from the string.

Regular Expressions¶

Regular expressions are ways of defining patterns of characters to be manipulated in some way from a larger string.

If you want to know more please see:

https://docs.python.org/3/library/re.html

The regular expression or regex is a pattern supplied to methods such as .str.extract().

The documentation for the .str.extract() method:

https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/reference/api/pandas.Series.str.extract.html

We must JOIN or MERGE the data sets to find out who painted the zero-feature paintings.

JOIN or MERGE¶

We need to use either the pd.merge() function or the .merge() method associated with a DataFrame object.

Basic syntax of joining is based on LEFT and RIGHT data sets.

pd.merge( <LEFT data>, <RIGHT data>, on=<KEYS>, how=<HOW to join?> )

I like to think the LEFT data set as the LARGER data that we are joining a smaller data set to.

The on argument corresponds to SHARED VARIABLES or SHARED COLUMNS that exist in both data sets.

INNER JOIN¶

This is the default option in pd.merge().

The KEY values are shared between the two data sets.

def find_missing_features(fname):
    return fname.isna().any()
